{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-jsx","path":"/fix-for-properly-displaying-images","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1 id=\"css-image-display-fix\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#css-image-display-fix\" aria-label=\"css image display fix permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>CSS Image DIsplay Fix</h1>\n<p>You might or might not have noticed this, but when you inspect images on a webpage using your Dev Tools, there's a small line underneath them, unless this was \"fixed\" by the developer.</p>\n<p>This is not really a bug. It happens because images are inline elements, and once you look at the image below, you'll begin getting the sense.</p>\n<div align=\"center\">\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 660px; \">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 53.93939393939393%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"baseline\" title=\"baseline\" src=\"/static/8c4f0c3f6489e302f6de69e02b4515d7/5ab81/baseline.jpg\" srcset=\"/static/8c4f0c3f6489e302f6de69e02b4515d7/e4e7a/baseline.jpg 165w,\n/static/8c4f0c3f6489e302f6de69e02b4515d7/4f5c6/baseline.jpg 330w,\n/static/8c4f0c3f6489e302f6de69e02b4515d7/5ab81/baseline.jpg 660w,\n/static/8c4f0c3f6489e302f6de69e02b4515d7/7ed05/baseline.jpg 990w,\n/static/8c4f0c3f6489e302f6de69e02b4515d7/e53e1/baseline.jpg 1162w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 660px) 100vw, 660px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n</div>\n<p>The green line is the <strong>baseline</strong>, an invisble line on which elements \"sit\". As you can see, some characters in the word <code class=\"language-text\">paragraph</code> go beyond this line, creating the red line you're seeing. And since images are inline elements, they \"sit\" on the baseline relative to elements before or after them, leaving a whitespace between their base and the space created by characters going beyond the baseline.</p>\n<p>To avoid this, just give the images a <code class=\"language-text\">display: &#39;block&#39;;</code></p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"html\"><pre class=\"language-html\"><code class=\"language-html\">img {\n   display: block;\n}</code></pre></div>\n<p>There, done! Now all images on your page won't have that annoying whitespace as they will fill it up.</p>","timeToRead":1,"excerpt":"CSS Image DIsplay Fix You might or might not have noticed this, but when you inspect images on a webpage using your Dev Tools, there's a…","frontmatter":{"title":"FIx for properly displaying images","date":"2020-10-26 17:27:18 +0100","categories":["other"],"tags":["CSS","Images","Image Display"],"description":null,"keywords":"CSS, Images, Image Display","author":"Rabson J Phiri","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":204,"height":132,"src":"/static/196a2651664d4af8da2ae6b5dce6a2a2/02521/other.png","srcSet":"/static/196a2651664d4af8da2ae6b5dce6a2a2/02521/other.png 1x"}}}},"fields":{"slug":"/fix-for-properly-displaying-images","date":"2020-10-26T16:27:18.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/fix-for-properly-displaying-images","nexttitle":"CSS Variables","nextslug":"/css-variables","prevtitle":"GitLens","p